title: Reports: Nats interview Baker for managerial opening
text:
Reports: Nats interview Dusty Baker for managerial opening The Washington Nationals have reportedly interviewed former Reds manager Dusty Baker to replace Matt Williams. Trent Rosecrans , crosecrans@enquirer.com 5:16 a.m. EDT October 15, 2015 
Former Reds manager Dusty Baker bumps fists with his players before the start of their Wild Card play-off game against the Pittsburgh Pirates last October. (Photo: The Enquirer/Gary Landers) 
Former Reds manager Dusty Baker interviewed for the vacant Washington Nationals job on Wednesday, according to several reports. 
The San Francisco Chronicle’s Bruce Jenkins was first to report Baker’s interview with the Nationals and it was later confirmed by James Wagner of the Washington Post. 
Other candidates being considered to replace Matt Williams include former Padres manager Bud Black, former Twins manager Ron Gardenhire. Black is scheduled to interview on Thursday, with Gardenhire to interview next week, according to Wagner. 
Diamondbacks Triple-A manager Phil Nevin interviewed on Monday, according to the Post and other candidates include Giants bench coach Ron Wotus and former big-leaguer Alex Cora. 
Baker, 66, was fired by the Reds after the team lost in the 2013 Wild Card Game in Pittsburgh. In six seasons as the Reds’ manager, Baker went 509-463 with three playoff trips. In the two years since Baker was fired, the Reds have gone 140-184 under Bryan Price, who served as Baker’s pitching coach from 2010 to 2013.
